Message.MsgText: registry.warning.invalid_ext=WSVR0703W: Invalid Extension id: {0}. The OSGi bundle cache might be stale of corrupt. To attempt to resolve this problem, run the osgiCfgInit utility with the -all option to reset all OSGi bundle caches, and then restart the application.
Message.Explanation: The extension ID was not found in the Eclipse extensions registry. The extension ID is undefined or the bundle which declares the extension ID failed to resolve during startup, possibly due to a stale or corrupt OSGi bundle cache.
Message.UserResponse: Run the osgiCfgInit utility with the -all option to reset all OSGi bundle caches, and then restart the failing application. If the problem persists, then see the troubleshooting information on the product web page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support.

Message.MsgText: WSVR0615W=WSVR0615W: The user.install.root system property is not set. Some product classes might not be found.
Message.Explanation: The Java invocation does not contain the user.install.root system property.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the user.install.root property on the Java invocation.

Message.MsgText: WSVR0710W=WSVR0710W: The {1} server is configured to use the {0} Java SDK, but this Java SDK version is not available. Instead, the server is starting with the version {2} Java runtime environment.
Message.Explanation: The server is configured to use a Java SDK that does not provide the version of the Java runtime environment on which the server is starting. On distributed operating systems, this condition can occur after the embedded Java SDK is updated or after swinging a profile to a product installation that uses a different embedded SDK. On z/OS, the condition can occur after mounting, or changing an intermediate symlink to, a configuration file system that connects to a product installation that does not have the Java SDK.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the Java SDK is installed in the target product installation, and enable the Java SDK on the server profile by using the managesdk command.

Message.MsgText: WSVR0617E_CANNOT_ACCESS_PLUGIN_DIR=WSVR0617E: The plugins directory cannot be accessed
Message.Explanation: The server start process is unable to read the plugins directory that is required to start the server. This error can occur if you do not have read permissions to the specified directory.
Message.UserResponse: Ensure that the user trying to start the server has sufficient read permissions to the specified directory.

Message.MsgText: WSVR0618E=WSVR0618E: The target application class failed to load
Message.Explanation: The start process cannot instantiate the application class. This error can occur when the Java invocation specifies an incorrect classpath, possibly because the script that launches the application changed. This error can also occur when a JAR file on the classpath is defective.
Message.UserResponse: If the application script file changed, restore the file and restart the failing application. If the problem persists, see the troubleshooting information on the product web page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support.
